  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC) - Requires member states to criminalize money laundering.\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank guidelines - Provide recommendations for preventing financial crimes.\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision - Offers principles for managing money laundering risks in banking.\n\n5. The Palermo Convention - An UN treaty focused on organized crime and money laundering prevention.\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, such as:\n- USA's Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- UK's Proceeds of Crime Act\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
